name: examples/dict_literal_not_closed.py
title: Dict Literal Not Closed
description:
When parsing code that contains unclosed parentheses or brackets the interpreter now includes the location of the unclosed bracket of parentheses.
In a similar way, errors involving unclosed string literals (single and triple quoted) now point to the start of the string instead of reporting EOF/EOL.
From the [Python3.10 release notes](https://docs.python.org/3/whatsnew/3.10.html#better-error-messages).
(Contributed by Pablo Galindo in [bpo-42864](https://bugs.python.org/issue?@action=redirect&bpo=42864) and Batuhan Taskaya in [bpo-40176](https://bugs.python.org/issue?@action=redirect&bpo=40176).)

name: examples/generator_without_parenthesis.py
title: Generator Without Parenthesis
description:
SyntaxError exceptions raised by the interpreter will now highlight the full error range of the expression that constitutes the syntax error itself, instead of just where the problem is detected.
From the [Python3.10 release notes](https://docs.python.org/3/whatsnew/3.10.html#better-error-messages).
(Contributed by Pablo Galindo in [bpo-43914](https://bugs.python.org/issue?@action=redirect&bpo=43914).)
